<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Transposing a Scale</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>To transpose a scale, start the scale on the note that is the tonic of the desired key.  For example, the major scale in the key of A starts on A.  Then add notes to the scale using the note intervals for the desired scale.  The intervals for the major scale are:  T-T-S-T-T-T-S.  So the A major scale is:  A B C# D E F# G# A.  Similarly, the intervals for the minor scale are:  T-S-T-T-S-T-T.  So the E minor scale is:  E F# G A B C D E.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Transposing scale patterns on the fretboard is pretty simple.  Just slide the patterns up or down the neck until the tonic notes in the pattern line up with the tonic notes of the desired scale.  Say you knew the major scale patterns in G and wanted to transpose them to A.  Just slide the patterns up 2 frets until the tonics fall on the A's:</P>
